/* Greatest exploits */ Change use of "his" for "the enemy's" to the less ambiguous "their". I understand the idiom that was used here, but using "he" for Wessel and "his" for the personification of "the enemy" in the same sentence is potentially confusing. People familiar with naval expressions in English would understand what was meant, but we have to consider other readers too.
